<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=magicianbalance&message.id=955#M955">14</a> of 26
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 491 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<P>Yeah,&nbsp;I was speaking in general terms.&nbsp; There is no need to get into the specific numbers.&nbsp; The bottom line is that the mage pet needs to be to the next best pet what the cleric heal is to the next best heal and what the wizard nuke is to the next best nuke.</P>
<P>I do completely agree with you, Shaman and Magician are the two classes that need the most work.&nbsp; I believe this is because of the Beastlord class.&nbsp; The bst has mage pet/dps abilities at around 90-100% of the mage class.&nbsp; The Bst has shm abilities at 80-90% of the shaman.&nbsp; This makes for a very powerful class.&nbsp; One I might add, that they stole shaman/mage roles from to create.&nbsp; Basically the only role they left us with is that of Malosinia/Malos, and Shaman/Magician have to compete for that.&nbsp;</P>
<P>With the current difficulty of the game, Shaman heals are not strong enough in the end game to be useful to groups, so the edge they have on Beastlords in that department is really worthless.&nbsp; Shaman slow is 10% greater than Beastlord slow, and Beastlords do very nearly the same damage as magicians.&nbsp; Beast buffs are quite good in comparison to a Shaman, so basically, groups would rather have the Beastlord because they get Mage damage with Shaman slow/buffs.&nbsp; To top it all off, they have the SD line of spells, which allows them to offer mana regen to a group, something that the mage barely does with mod rods, and that the Shaman doesn't do.&nbsp; In addition, the Beastlord can buff his pet with the various procs that he wants, giving him more control over the usefulness of his pet than a mage has.</P>
<P>The fix for mages, is to increase mage pets to the point where they blow all other pets out of the water, and allow mages to turn their pets procs on and off.&nbsp; A general overall increase in dps of the mage so that Beastlords cannot rival it in group or raid settings also needs to be done.</P>
<P>Quite honestly I don't know what they should do to fix the Shaman.&nbsp; The only thing I can think of is to increase the shaman slow to 85% or something, while at the same time nerfing the Beastlord slows and buffs.&nbsp; This would make the Beastlord class more of a fill all position if either DPS or Slow couldn't be found.&nbsp; I don't like asking for nerfs on other classes though, so I think this is a terrible solution.</P>
<P>Personally I thnk the dev's need to put as much attention into fixing Magicians and Shamans as they did into creating the Beastlord.&nbsp; I mean really, they took a host of magician ideas for mage balance and created the Beastlord class from them.&nbsp; It was really quite upsetting.</P>
<P>I don't know what is happening in Shamanland, but I can tell you that Mages are the least played class in the game, with more quitting everyday.&nbsp; If Shaman's are quitting everyday as well, perhaps it is time for a Magician/Shaman alliance to demand SOE return us to our group/raid roles that the Beastlord usurped.</P>
<P>I wish the Shamans the best of luck.&nbsp; I am guessing SOE will ignore them only slightly less than they ignore Magicians though.</P>
<DIV></DIV>	
		</td></tr>
